FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, IMPALA - SOUTH AFRICA
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Sat, 13 Jun 1998
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslary@fas.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties

An emergency report was received on 8 June from Dr P.P. Bosman, Chief
Director of Veterinary Services and Livestock Improvement, Pretoria, on an
outbreak of foot and mouth disease in the Kruger National Park and an
adjacent private game reserve incorporated into the park.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, postmortem and laboratory. Date of initial
detection of animal health incident: 22 May 1998. Estimated date of first
infection: 15 May 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
24o 27' S - 31o 24' E 1
Description of affected population: impala (_Aepyceros melampus_). Total
number of susceptible animals in the outbreak: 10,000
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Onderstepoort Institute for Exotic
Diseases.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation and PCR.
C. Causal agent: FMD virus serotype SAT1.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: carrier African buffalo
(_Syncerus caffer_).
B. Mode of spread: direct contact.
C. Other epidemiological details: the outbreak occurred within the FMD
enzootic area of South Africa (Kruger National Park). No marketing of
susceptible game animals or their products is allowed from this area.
Control measures during reporting period: normal zoo sanitary measures
instituted; strict movement control applied in the adjacent farming area;
export of animals and animal products from the free zone not affected.
--
